%N A059106 Number of solutions to Nickerson variant of Langford (or Langford-Skolem) problem.
%C A059106 How many ways are of arranging the numbers 1,1,2,2,3,3,...,n,n so that there are zero numbers between the two 1's, one number between the two 2's, ..., n-1 numbers between the two n's?
%C A059106 For n > 1, a(n) = A004075(n)/2 because A004075 also counts reflected solutions. - _Martin Fuller_, Mar 08 2007
%C A059106 Because of symmetry, is a(5) = 5 the largest prime in this sequence? - _Jonathan Vos Post_, Apr 02 2011
%H A059106 Ali Assarpour, Amotz Bar-Noy, Ou Liuo, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1507.00315">Counting the Number of Langford Skolem Pairings</a>, arXiv:1507.00315 [cs.DM], 2015.
